<subSubSection id="6D837C85103EFFA6DBB2FB7F4D542CBE" lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="129" pageId="27" pageNumber="128" type="description">
<paragraph id="25262F0E103EFFA1DBB2FB7F4DA32F63" blockId="27.[151,501,1039,1102]" box="[151,406,1076,1102]" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">
(
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B103EFFA1DBBAFB7F4D142F63" box="[159,289,1076,1102]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–22" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1805,1829]" captionTargetBox="[158,1424,181,1782]" captionTargetId="figure-17@5.[158,1430,181,1782]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11–22. Asianthrips species. A. magnus, 11–12; (11) Female (mac); (12) Female (mic). A. malayanus, 13–14; (13), Female (mac); (14) Non-paratypic female (mic). A. nobilis, 15–16; (15) Female (mac); (16) Female (mic). A. orientalis, 17–18; (17) Female (mac); (18) Male (mic). A. pallens, 19–20; (19) Female (mac); (20) Male (mic). A. parvinotus, 21–22; (21) Female (mac); (22) Male, non-paratype (mic)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404870" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404870/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">Figs 21–22</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B103EFFA1DA09FB7F4DBB2F63" box="[300,398,1076,1102]" captionStart="FIGURES 117–123" captionStartId="28.[151,264,1591,1615]" captionTargetBox="[158,1429,273,1568]" captionTargetId="figure-75@28.[158,1429,273,1568]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURES 117–123. Asianthrips parvinotus, sp. n. (117) Head–pelta (female, mac); (118) Head–tergite II (male non-paratype, mic); (119) Antenna (female, mac); (120) Basantra–mesopresternum (female, mac); (121) Tergite III (female, mac); (122) Tergite III (male, mic); (123) Tube (female, mac)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404918" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404918/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">117–123</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="25262F0E103EFFA1DBB2FB374DAF2DD7" blockId="27.[151,1437,1148,2039]" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C103EFFA1DBB2FB374D412FBB" box="[151,372,1148,1174]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">Female macroptera</emphasis>
. Body brown (
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B103EFFA1D938FB374E452FBB" box="[541,624,1148,1174]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–22" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1805,1829]" captionTargetBox="[158,1424,181,1782]" captionTargetId="figure-17@5.[158,1430,181,1782]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11–22. Asianthrips species. A. magnus, 11–12; (11) Female (mac); (12) Female (mic). A. malayanus, 13–14; (13), Female (mac); (14) Non-paratypic female (mic). A. nobilis, 15–16; (15) Female (mac); (16) Female (mic). A. orientalis, 17–18; (17) Female (mac); (18) Male (mic). A. pallens, 19–20; (19) Female (mac); (20) Male (mic). A. parvinotus, 21–22; (21) Female (mac); (22) Male, non-paratype (mic)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404870" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404870/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
). Antennal segment III yellow, often shaded with pale brown, remaining segments uniformly brown. All femora brown, concolourous with body, with extreme apices yellowish; all tibiae and tarsi yellow. Fore wings weakly shaded with brown at basal half. Body setae almost colourless. Head (
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B103EFFA1DE13FB8F49A12FF3" box="[1334,1428,1220,1246]" captionStart="FIGURES 117–123" captionStartId="28.[151,264,1591,1615]" captionTargetBox="[158,1429,273,1568]" captionTargetId="figure-75@28.[158,1429,273,1568]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURES 117–123. Asianthrips parvinotus, sp. n. (117) Head–pelta (female, mac); (118) Head–tergite II (male non-paratype, mic); (119) Antenna (female, mac); (120) Basantra–mesopresternum (female, mac); (121) Tergite III (female, mac); (122) Tergite III (male, mic); (123) Tube (female, mac)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404918" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404918/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">Fig. 117</figureCitation>
) longer than wide, about 1.1 times as long as wide in 
<typeStatus id="FA2291AC103EFFA1D9CBFBA34F612E2F" box="[750,852,1256,1282]" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">holotype</typeStatus>
; dorsal surface generally sculptured with transverse reticulation, but ocellar triangle with very weak polygonal reticulation. Cheeks very weakly rounded, weakly narrowed to base, but they are almost straight and parallel-sided in compressed specimens. Postocular setae almost as long as eyes or a little shorter. Postocellar setae almost as long as a diameter of posterior ocellus. Eyes well developed, 0.43 times as long as head in 
<typeStatus id="FA2291AC103EFFA1D948FA334EE62EBF" box="[621,723,1400,1426]" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">holotype</typeStatus>
. Antennal segments VII and VIII somewhat broadly fused, but VIII not constricted basally, cone-shaped (
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B103EFFA1D95CFAD74EE92E9B" box="[633,732,1436,1462]" captionStart="FIGURES 117–123" captionStartId="28.[151,264,1591,1615]" captionTargetBox="[158,1429,273,1568]" captionTargetId="figure-75@28.[158,1429,273,1568]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURES 117–123. Asianthrips parvinotus, sp. n. (117) Head–pelta (female, mac); (118) Head–tergite II (male non-paratype, mic); (119) Antenna (female, mac); (120) Basantra–mesopresternum (female, mac); (121) Tergite III (female, mac); (122) Tergite III (male, mic); (123) Tube (female, mac)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404918" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404918/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">Fig. 119</figureCitation>
); segment III with three sense cones. Maxillary stylets almost reaching postocular setae, rather wide apart, a little wider than 1/3 of the head width apart at the basal collar of head. Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B103EFFA1DA78FAAF4D8B2ED3" box="[349,446,1508,1534]" captionStart="FIGURES 117–123" captionStartId="28.[151,264,1591,1615]" captionTargetBox="[158,1429,273,1568]" captionTargetId="figure-75@28.[158,1429,273,1568]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURES 117–123. Asianthrips parvinotus, sp. n. (117) Head–pelta (female, mac); (118) Head–tergite II (male non-paratype, mic); (119) Antenna (female, mac); (120) Basantra–mesopresternum (female, mac); (121) Tergite III (female, mac); (122) Tergite III (male, mic); (123) Tube (female, mac)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404918" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404918/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">Fig. 117</figureCitation>
) 0.58 times as long as head and 2.16 times as wide as long in 
<typeStatus id="FA2291AC103EFFA1DFBFFAAF49352ED3" box="[1178,1280,1508,1534]" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">holotype</typeStatus>
; pa about 3/4 of the median pronotal length. Metanotum (
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B103EFFA1D9ACF9434EDC2D0F" box="[649,745,1544,1570]" captionStart="FIGURES 117–123" captionStartId="28.[151,264,1591,1615]" captionTargetBox="[158,1429,273,1568]" captionTargetId="figure-75@28.[158,1429,273,1568]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURES 117–123. Asianthrips parvinotus, sp. n. (117) Head–pelta (female, mac); (118) Head–tergite II (male non-paratype, mic); (119) Antenna (female, mac); (120) Basantra–mesopresternum (female, mac); (121) Tergite III (female, mac); (122) Tergite III (male, mic); (123) Tube (female, mac)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404918" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404918/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">Fig. 117</figureCitation>
) polygonally reticulated anteriorly, longitudinally reticulated posteriorly. Prospinasternum rather small. Mesopresternum and mesoeusternum (
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B103EFFA1DF0EF96748B92D6B" box="[1067,1164,1580,1606]" captionStart="FIGURES 117–123" captionStartId="28.[151,264,1591,1615]" captionTargetBox="[158,1429,273,1568]" captionTargetId="figure-75@28.[158,1429,273,1568]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURES 117–123. Asianthrips parvinotus, sp. n. (117) Head–pelta (female, mac); (118) Head–tergite II (male non-paratype, mic); (119) Antenna (female, mac); (120) Basantra–mesopresternum (female, mac); (121) Tergite III (female, mac); (122) Tergite III (male, mic); (123) Tube (female, mac)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404918" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404918/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">Fig. 120</figureCitation>
) widely fused medially, with very short sutures between them at both sides. Fore tarsi unarmed. Fore wings with 6–7 duplicated cilia in 
<typeStatus id="FA2291AC103EFFA1DBB2F93F4CC82DA3" box="[151,253,1652,1678]" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">holotype</typeStatus>
. Tergites rather small, especially tergites III–V very narrow (
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B103EFFA1D8E2F93F48192DA3" box="[967,1068,1652,1678]" captionStart="FIGURES 117–123" captionStartId="28.[151,264,1591,1615]" captionTargetBox="[158,1429,273,1568]" captionTargetId="figure-75@28.[158,1429,273,1568]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURES 117–123. Asianthrips parvinotus, sp. n. (117) Head–pelta (female, mac); (118) Head–tergite II (male non-paratype, mic); (119) Antenna (female, mac); (120) Basantra–mesopresternum (female, mac); (121) Tergite III (female, mac); (122) Tergite III (male, mic); (123) Tube (female, mac)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404918" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404918/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">Fig. 121</figureCitation>
), much narrower than sternites, narrower than pronotum. S1 and S2 setae on tergite IX subequal in length, about 3/4 the length of tube, S1 weakly expanded, S2 very weakly expanded or nearly pointed at apex. Tube (
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B103EFFA1D8B2F9F74FC32DFB" box="[919,1014,1724,1750]" captionStart="FIGURES 117–123" captionStartId="28.[151,264,1591,1615]" captionTargetBox="[158,1429,273,1568]" captionTargetId="figure-75@28.[158,1429,273,1568]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURES 117–123. Asianthrips parvinotus, sp. n. (117) Head–pelta (female, mac); (118) Head–tergite II (male non-paratype, mic); (119) Antenna (female, mac); (120) Basantra–mesopresternum (female, mac); (121) Tergite III (female, mac); (122) Tergite III (male, mic); (123) Tube (female, mac)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404918" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404918/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">Fig. 123</figureCitation>
) about 0.6 times as long as head. Anal setae shorter than tube.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="25262F0E103EFFA1DBE2F84F4E132CFF" blockId="27.[151,1437,1148,2039]" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C103EFFA1DBE2F84F4D432C33" bold="true" box="[199,374,1796,1822]" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">Measurements</emphasis>
. Female 
<typeStatus id="FA2291AC103EFFA1DAC0F84F4E722C33" box="[485,583,1796,1822]" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">holotype</typeStatus>
(mac.) in microns. Distended body length 1825. Head length 175, width across cheeks 159. Compound eye dorsal length about 75. Pronotum length 106, width 218. Abdominal tergite IV median width 205. Fore wing length about 750. Tube length 106, width across base 55. Antenna length about 400, segments III–VIII length (width) as follows: 58 (29), 65 (27), 57 (25), 53 (22), 47 (19), 35 (12). Postocular setae 72–74. Pronotal aa 50–52, am 56–58, ml 64–70, pa 75–78, epim 60–64. S1 setae on tergite IX 78–80, S2 setae on tergite IX 78–82. Anal setae 90–92.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="25262F0E103EFFA6DBE2F8974E5B2BD4" blockId="27.[151,1437,1148,2039]" lastBlockId="28.[151,1436,151,249]" lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="129" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C103EFFA1DBE2F8974DA52CDB" box="[199,400,2012,2038]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">Male macroptera</emphasis>
. Very similar in colour and structure to macropterous female (
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B103EFFA1DFA6F89748E92CDB" box="[1155,1244,2012,2038]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–22" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1805,1829]" captionTargetBox="[158,1424,181,1782]" captionTargetId="figure-17@5.[158,1430,181,1782]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11–22. Asianthrips species. A. magnus, 11–12; (11) Female (mac); (12) Female (mic). A. malayanus, 13–14; (13), Female (mac); (14) Non-paratypic female (mic). A. nobilis, 15–16; (15) Female (mac); (16) Female (mic). A. orientalis, 17–18; (17) Female (mac); (18) Male (mic). A. pallens, 19–20; (19) Female (mac); (20) Male (mic). A. parvinotus, 21–22; (21) Female (mac); (22) Male, non-paratype (mic)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404870" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404870/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="128">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
), except for the followings: Body smaller; pronotal posteroangular setae not so long, almost as long as epimerals; fore wing with 5–6 duplicated cilia; S1 setae on tergite IX 0.83–0.89 times as long as tube, S2 setae short and pointed; tube 0.56 times as long as head. Fore tarsi unarmed.
</paragraph>
<caption id="71E67F861039FFA6DBB2F97C4EA52DBA" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404918" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6404918" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404918/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="129" startId="28.[151,264,1591,1615]" targetBox="[158,1429,273,1568]" targetPageId="28">
<paragraph id="25262F0E1039FFA6DBB2F97C4EA52DBA" blockId="28.[151,1437,1591,1687]" pageId="28" pageNumber="129">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C1039FFA6DBB2F97C4D592D62" bold="true" box="[151,364,1591,1615]" pageId="28" pageNumber="129">FIGURES 117–123.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="E299548D1039FFA6DA57F97C4E6C2D62" authority="Okajima &amp; Masumoto, 2022" authorityName="Okajima &amp; Masumoto" authorityYear="2022" box="[370,601,1591,1615]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Asianthrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parvinotus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C1039FFA6DA57F97C4E6C2D62" box="[370,601,1591,1615]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="129">Asianthrips parvinotus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis id="17EDF31C1039FFA6D943F97C4EAA2D62" bold="true" box="[614,671,1591,1615]" pageId="28" pageNumber="129">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="0CDE4E671039FFA6D943F97C4EAA2D62" box="[614,671,1591,1615]" pageId="28" pageNumber="129" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(117) Head–pelta (female, mac); (118) Head–tergite II (male non-paratype, mic); (119) Antenna (female, mac); (120) Basantra–mesopresternum (female, mac); (121) Tergite III (female, mac); (122) Tergite III (male, mic); (123) Tube (female, mac).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="25262F0E1039FFA6DBE2F98E4D542CBE" blockId="28.[151,1437,1733,2012]" pageId="28" pageNumber="129">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C1039FFA6DBE2F98E4D432DF2" bold="true" box="[199,374,1733,1759]" pageId="28" pageNumber="129">Measurements</emphasis>
. Male 
<typeStatus id="FA2291AC1039FFA6DAE3F98D4E132DCD" box="[454,550,1734,1760]" pageId="28" pageNumber="129">paratype</typeStatus>
(mac.) in microns. Distended body length about 1500. Head length 162, width across cheeks 152. Compound eye dorsal length 68. Pronotum length 88, width 205. Abdominal tergite IV median width 184. Fore wing length about 690. Tube length 90, width across base 47. Antenna length 375, segments III– VIII length (width) as follows: 55 (28), 58 (26), 52 (24), 52 (22), 43 (20), 30 (12). Postocular setae 62–63. Pronotal aa 39–40, am 45–47, ml 52–53, pa 52–53, epim 50–54. S1 setae on tergite IX 75–80, S2 setae on tergite IX 30–32. Anal setae 80–82.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
